.SH "TredMacro"
.IX Header "TredMacro"
TredMacro (\fItred.def\fR) \- implements the public \s-1API\s0 for TrEd/bTred macros
.SS "Global variables"
.IX Subsection "Global variables"
.ie n .IP "$this" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$this\fR" 4
.IX Item "$this"
Current node (i.e. the active node in TrEd and the node in turn if
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-N\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`\-H\*(C'\fR flag was used in bTrEd). Assigning a different node
from the current tree to this variable results in changing the active
node in TrEd and continuing processing at that node in bTrEd.
.ie n .IP "$root" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$root\fR" 4
.IX Item "$root"
Root of the current tree. If possible, avoid changing this variable in
a macro, so that called macros may rely on its value too.
.ie n .IP "$FileChanged (alias $FileNotSaved \- still valid but obsolete)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$FileChanged\fR (alias \f(CW$FileNotSaved\fR \- still valid but obsolete)" 4
.IX Item "$FileChanged (alias $FileNotSaved - still valid but obsolete)"
See also \f(CW\*(C`ChangingFile()\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
If this variable is set to 1, TrEd/bTrEd considers the current file to
be modified and in case of bTrEd makes the program to save it before
it is closed (in case of TrEd, user is prompted before the file is
closed). If the macro does not change this variable, bTrEd does not
change the file status, while TrEd still assumes that the file \fBwas\fR
modified. In other words, set this variable to 1 in bTrEd if you want
the file to be saved at last, and set this variable to 0 in TrEd if
you are sure you did not make any change to the file that would be
worth saving it. As there is a danger that calling one macro from
another may result in a mess in the value of \f(CW$FileChanged\fR it is
adviced to use the default macro \f(CW\*(C`ChangingFile()\*(C'\fR which tries to set
the file status only if really intended (see below).
.ie n .IP "$Redraw" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$Redraw\fR" 4
.IX Item "$Redraw"
This variable makes sense only in TrEd.  You may set it to one of
\&\f(CW\*(C`file\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`tree\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`win\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`all\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`tie\*(C'\fR to alter the mechanism of redrawing the
screen. The default value is \f(CW\*(C`file\*(C'\fR (redraw all windows displaying
current file), while \f(CW\*(C`tree\*(C'\fR means redraw all windows displaying
current tree, \f(CW\*(C`win\*(C'\fR means redraw only current window and \f(CW\*(C`tie\*(C'\fR means
redraw all if windows are tied or (if not) redraw only current window.
To disable redrawing set this variable to \f(CW\*(C`none\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP "$forceFileSaved" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$forceFileSaved\fR" 4
.IX Item "$forceFileSaved"
In TrEd, you may wish to set this variable to 0 if you wish to change
the status of the file to \f(CW\*(C`saved\*(C'\fR (e.g. after saving the file from
your macro).
.ie n .IP "$libDir" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$libDir\fR" 4
.IX Item "$libDir"
This variable contains a path to TrEd library directory.
.SS "Navigation"
.IX Subsection "Navigation"
Methods of Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm> objects should be used for basic navigation within
trees. Here are described means to navigate from one tree to another
and a few extra macros for specific navigation in trees.
.ie n .IP "GotoTree(n)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGotoTree(n)\fR" 4
.IX Item "GotoTree(n)"
Display the n'th tree in the current file.
The number of the first tree for this function is 1.
.ie n .IP "TieGotoTree(n)" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWTieGotoTree(n)\fR" 4
.IX Item "TieGotoTree(n)"
Go to n'th tree in all tied windows.
The number of the first tree for this function is 1.
.ie n .IP """TieNextTree()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWTieNextTree()\fR" 4
.IX Item "TieNextTree()"
Display the next tree in all tied windows.
.ie n .IP """TiePrevTree()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWTiePrevTree()\fR" 4
.IX Item "TiePrevTree()"
Display the previous tree in all tied windows.
.ie n .IP """NextTree()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNextTree()\fR" 4
.IX Item "NextTree()"
Display the next tree in the current file.
.ie n .IP """PrevTree()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPrevTree()\fR" 4
.IX Item "PrevTree()"
Display the previous tree in the current file.
.ie n .IP """GetTrees()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetTrees()\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetTrees()"
Return a list of trees in current Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm>. Equivallent to
\&\f(CW\*(C`CurrentFile()\->trees\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """GetSecondaryFiles($fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetSecondaryFiles($fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetSecondaryFiles($fsfile?)"
Return a list of secondary Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> objects for the given (or current)
file.  A secondary file is a file required by a file to be loaded
along with it; this is typical for files containing some form of a
stand-off annotation where one tree is built upon another. Note
however, that this does not include so called knitting \- an operation
where the stand-off annotation is handled by a \s-1IO\s0 backend and the
resulting knitted file appears to btred as a single unit.
Only those secondary files that are already open are returned.
.ie n .IP """NextNode(node,top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNextNode(node,top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NextNode(node,top?)"
Return the first displayed node following the given node in the
subtree of top. This function behaves in the same manner as the
node\->following(top) method, except it works only on the nodes which
are actually visible according to the state of the View\->Show Hidden
Nodes menu item.
.ie n .IP """PrevNode(node,top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPrevNode(node,top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PrevNode(node,top?)"
Return the first displayed node preceding the given node in the
subtree of top. This function behaves in the same manner as the
node\->previous(top) method, except it works only on the nodes which
are actually visible according to the state of the View\->Show Hidden
Nodes menu item.
.ie n .IP """NextVisibleNode(node,top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNextVisibleNode(node,top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NextVisibleNode(node,top?)"
Return the first visible node following the given node in the subtree
of top. This function behaves in the same manner as the
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->following($top)\*(C'\fR method, except that nodes of hidden subtrees
are skipped.
.ie n .IP """PrevVisibleNode(node,top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPrevVisibleNode(node,top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PrevVisibleNode(node,top?)"
Return the first visible node preceding the given node in the subtree
of top. This function behaves in the same manner as the
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->previous($top)\*(C'\fR method, except that nodes of hidden subtrees
are skipped.
.ie n .IP """IsHidden(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWIsHidden(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "IsHidden(node)"
Return true if the given node is member of a hidden subtree. This
macro is only an abbreviation for
\&\f(CW\*(C`FS()\->isHidden(node)\*(C'\fR
.ie n .IP """Hide(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWHide(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "Hide(node)"
Hide a given node.
.ie n .IP """GetNodes(top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetNodes(top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetNodes(top?)"
Get a list of all nodes in the current tree or (if top is given) in
the subtree of top (the root of the tree is icluded as well). The list
returned is ordered in the depth-first ordering.
(This function automatically returns array reference in scalar context.)
.ie n .IP """GetVisibleNodes(top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetVisibleNodes(top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetVisibleNodes(top?)"
Return the list of all visible nodes in the subtree of the given top
node (or the whole current tree if no top is given). The list returned
is ordered in the depth-first ordering and all members of hidden
subtrees are skipped.
.ie n .IP """GetDisplayedNodes($win?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetDisplayedNodes($win?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetDisplayedNodes($win?)"
Return the list of all nodes actually currently displayed in the
current window in TrEd (which nodes are actually displayed can be
e.g. specified with get_nodelist_hook).
.ie n .IP """PrevNodeLinear(node,attribute,top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPrevNodeLinear(node,attribute,top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PrevNodeLinear(node,attribute,top?)"
Returns nearest node in the tree preceding the given node in linear
ordering provided by the given attribute. If top node is present, only
a subtree of top is examined.
.ie n .IP """NextNodeLinear(node,attribute,top?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNextNodeLinear(node,attribute,top?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NextNodeLinear(node,attribute,top?)"
Returns nearest node in the tree following the given node in linear
ordering provided by the given attribute. If top node is present, only
a subtree of top is examined.
.ie n .IP """CurrentTreeNumber( $win? )""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCurrentTreeNumber( $win? )\fR" 4
.IX Item "CurrentTreeNumber( $win? )"
Return current tree number.  Note that the number of the first tree if
file reported by this function is 0, so you have to add 1 before
passing the number to functions like GotoTree.  If used in TrEd,
optional argument win can be used to specify TrEd window (defaults to
the current window).
.ie n .IP """GetNodeIndex()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetNodeIndex()\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetNodeIndex()"
Return given node's position in the deep-first tree ordering.
.ie n .IP """LocateNode(node?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWLocateNode(node?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "LocateNode(node?,fsfile?)"
Return current filename, index of a tree (starting from 1) in the file
to which the node belongs (0 if not found) and node's position in the tree
in the deep-first tree ordering.
.Sp
If \f(CW\*(C`node\*(C'\fR is not given, \f(CW$this\fR is assumed. Should the node be from a
different file than the current one, the second argument must specify
the corresponding Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """ThisAddress(node?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWThisAddress(node?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ThisAddress(node?,fsfile?)"
Return a given node's address string in a form of
filename#tree_no.index (tree_no starts from 1 to reflect TrEd's \s-1UI\s0
convention).  If the correct tree number could not be determined (the
node does not belong to any top-level tree in the file) and the node
has an \s-1ID\s0, the address is returned in the form filename#ID.
.Sp
If \f(CW\*(C`node\*(C'\fR is not given, \f(CW$this\fR is assumed. Should the node be from a
different file than the current one, the second argument must specify
the corresponding Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """ThisAddressNTRED(node?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWThisAddressNTRED(node?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ThisAddressNTRED(node?,fsfile?)"
Return a given node's address string in a form of
ntred://filename@tree_no#1.index (tree_no starts from 1 to reflect
TrEd's \s-1UI\s0 convention). If the correct tree number could not be
determined (the node does not belong to any top-level tree in the
file) and the node has an \s-1ID\s0, the address is returned in the form
ntred://filename#ID.
.Sp
The returned address may be opened in TrEd to examine the tree in
memory of a remote btred server.
.Sp
If \f(CW\*(C`node\*(C'\fR is not given, \f(CW$this\fR is assumed. Should the node be from a
different file than the current one, the second argument must specify
the corresponding Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """FPosition(node?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWFPosition(node?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "FPosition(node?,fsfile?)"
Prints the result of \f(CW\*(C`ThisAddress\*(C'\fR on stdout.
.ie n .IP """NPosition(node?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNPosition(node?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NPosition(node?,fsfile?)"
Prints the result of \f(CW\*(C`ThisAddressNTRED\*(C'\fR on stdout.
.ie n .IP """ParseNodeAddress(address)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWParseNodeAddress(address)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ParseNodeAddress(address)"
Split given address into a filename/URL and a suffix and return these
as a two element list.
.SS "Tree editing \s-1API\s0"
.IX Subsection "Tree editing API"
.ie n .IP """CutPaste(node,new\-parent)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCutPaste(node,new\-parent)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CutPaste(node,new-parent)"
Cut given node (including its subtree) and paste it to a new
parent. This macro is safer than PasteNode since it checks that
new-parent is not a descendant of node or node itself. If the check
fails, the macro dies with an error before any change is made.
.Sp
Note: this macro does not verify node types. Use
\&\f(CW\*(C`$parent\->test_child_type($node)\*(C'\fR to be sure that type declarations permit 
the node as a child node of the new parent.
.ie n .IP """CutPasteBefore(node,ref_node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCutPasteBefore(node,ref_node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CutPasteBefore(node,ref_node)"
Cut given node (including its subtree) nd paste it on ref_node's
parent node just before ref_node. This macro is safer than
PasteNodeBefore since it checks that new-parent is not a descendant of
node or node itself. This macro dies on error before any change is
made.
.Sp
Note: this macro does not verify node types. Use
\&\f(CW\*(C`$parent\->test_child_type($node)\*(C'\fR to be sure that type declarations permit 
the node as a child node of the new parent.
.ie n .IP """CutPasteAfter(node,ref_node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCutPasteAfter(node,ref_node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CutPasteAfter(node,ref_node)"
Cut given node (including its subtree) and paste it on ref_node's parent node just after
ref_node. This macro is safer than PasteNodeBefore since it checks
that new-parent is not a descendant of node or node itself. This macro
dies on error before any change is made.
.Sp
Note: this macro does not verify node types. Use
\&\f(CW\*(C`$parent\->test_child_type($node)\*(C'\fR to be sure that type declarations permit 
the node as a child node of the new parent.
.ie n .IP """PasteNode(node,new\-parent)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPasteNode(node,new\-parent)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PasteNode(node,new-parent)"
Paste the subtree of the node under the new-parent.  The root of the
subtree is placed among other children of new-parent with respect to
the numbering attribute.
.Sp
Note: this macro does not verify node types. Use
\&\f(CW\*(C`$parent\->test_child_type($node)\*(C'\fR to be sure that type declarations permit 
the node as a child node of the new parent.
.ie n .IP """PasteNodeBefore(node,ref_node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPasteNodeBefore(node,ref_node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PasteNodeBefore(node,ref_node)"
Cut given node (including its subtree) and paste it on ref_node's
parent node just before ref_node.
.Sp
Note: this macro does not verify node types. Use
\&\f(CW\*(C`$parent\->test_child_type($node)\*(C'\fR to be sure that type declarations permit 
the node as a child node of the new parent.
.ie n .IP """PasteNodeAfter(node,ref_node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPasteNodeAfter(node,ref_node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PasteNodeAfter(node,ref_node)"
Cut given node (including its subtree) and paste it on ref_node's
parent node just after ref_node.
.Sp
Note: this macro does not verify node types. Use
\&\f(CW\*(C`$parent\->test_child_type($node)\*(C'\fR to be sure that type declarations permit 
the node as a child node of the new parent.
.ie n .IP """CloneSubtree(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCloneSubtree(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CloneSubtree(node)"
Return an identical copy (except that only declared attributes are
preserved) of the given subtree.
.ie n .IP """CopyNode(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCopyNode(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CopyNode(node)"
Return an identical copy (except that only declared attributes are
preserved) of the given node. The input node must belong to the
current file.
.ie n .IP """CutNode(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCutNode(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CutNode(node)"
Cut the node's subtree off the tree and return it. By cuttin a subtree
we mean disconnecting it from the rest of the tree. Use PasteNode to
attach it to some node again.
.ie n .IP """NewTree()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNewTree()\fR" 4
.IX Item "NewTree()"
Create a new tree before the current tree. The new tree consists of
exactly one node. This node is activated and a reference to its Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm>
object is returned.
.ie n .IP """NewTreeAfter()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNewTreeAfter()\fR" 4
.IX Item "NewTreeAfter()"
Create a new tree after the current tree. The new tree consists of
exactly one node. This node is activated and a reference to its Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm>
object is returned.
.ie n .IP """NewRBrother(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNewRBrother(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NewRBrother(node)"
Create a new brother of the given node and recalculate the special \s-1FS\s0
numbering attribute values in the whole tree so that the new node is
the first right sibling of the given node.
.Sp
If no node is given, this function operates on \f(CW$this\fR and \fBresets\fR
\&\f(CW$this\fR to the newly created node. If some node is given the value
of \f(CW$this\fR is preserved.
.ie n .IP """NewLBrother(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNewLBrother(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NewLBrother(node)"
Create a new brother of the given node and recalculate the special \s-1FS\s0
numbering attribute values in the whole tree so that the new node is
the first left sibling of the given node.
.Sp
If no node is given, this function operates on \f(CW$this\fR and \fBresets\fR
\&\f(CW$this\fR to the newly created node. If some node is given the value
of \f(CW$this\fR is preserved.
.ie n .IP """NewSon(parent)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNewSon(parent)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NewSon(parent)"
Create a new child of the given parent node and recalculate the
special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute values in the whole tree so that the
new node is the first node right to the given parent.
.Sp
If no parent node is given, this function operates on \f(CW$this\fR and
\&\fBresets\fR \f(CW$this\fR to the newly created node. If a parent node is
given the value of \f(CW$this\fR is preserved.
.ie n .IP """NewParent(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNewParent(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NewParent(node)"
Create a node between given node and its parent and recalculate the
special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute values in the whole tree so that the
new node is the first node left to the given node.
.Sp
If no node is given, this function operates on \f(CW$this\fR and
\&\fBresets\fR \f(CW$this\fR to the newly created node. If a parent node is
given the value of \f(CW$this\fR is preserved.
.ie n .IP """DeleteThisNode()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWDeleteThisNode()\fR" 4
.IX Item "DeleteThisNode()"
Delete the current (\f(CW$this\fR) node and recalculate the special \s-1FS\s0
numbering attribute values in the whole tree so that there is no gap
in the numbering. If the current node is not a leaf or if it is the
root of the current tree, this macro does nothing.
.ie n .IP """DeleteLeafNode(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWDeleteLeafNode(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "DeleteLeafNode(node)"
Delete a leaf node and recalculate the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute
values in the whole tree so that there is no gap in the numbering. If
a given node is not a leaf, this macro does nothing.
.ie n .IP """DeleteSubtree(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWDeleteSubtree(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "DeleteSubtree(node)"
Deletes a whole node's subtree and recalculate the special \s-1FS\s0
numbering attribute values in the whole tree so that there is no gap
in the numbering.
.ie n .IP """RemoveTree(n?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRemoveTree(n?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "RemoveTree(n?,fsfile?)"
Removes n\-th tree from a given Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> (trees are numbered starting from 0).
If no Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> is specified, uses the current file (see \fICurrentFile()\fR).
.Sp
Calling \fIRemoveTree()\fR without arguments, it is equivalent to
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&  RemoveTree(CurrentTreeNumber(),CurrentFile())
.Ve
.Sp
Returns the deleted tree. If you do not reattatch the tree to the Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm>,
use \f(CW$tree\fR\->destroy method on the returned tree to prevent a memory leak.
.ie n .IP """DestroyTree(n?,fsfile?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWDestroyTree(n?,fsfile?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "DestroyTree(n?,fsfile?)"
Like RemoveTree but immediatelly destroys the removed tree. Returns 1
on success.
.ie n .IP """DetermineNodeType($node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWDetermineNodeType($node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "DetermineNodeType($node)"
For trees with Treex::PML::Schema <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Schema.pm>\-based node typing, try to determine the type
of the node from the type of its parent, and associate the node with
the type (using \f(CW$node\fR\->set_type). If there are more possibilities, the
user is asked to choose the correct type.
.ie n .IP """CopyValues()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCopyValues()\fR" 4
.IX Item "CopyValues()"
Copy the values of all the attributes except the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering
attribute of the current node to a global hash variable named
\&\f(CW%ValuesClipboard\fR.
.ie n .IP """PasteValues()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPasteValues()\fR" 4
.IX Item "PasteValues()"
Replace existing values of the current node's attributes by all values
stored in the global hash variable named \f(CW%ValuesClipboard\fR. The
function does not perform any node-type validity checks.
.ie n .IP """PlainNewSon(parent)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPlainNewSon(parent)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PlainNewSon(parent)"
Add a new child node to the given parent and make it the current
node (by setting \f(CW$this\fR to point to it).
.ie n .IP """PlainDeleteNode()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPlainDeleteNode()\fR" 4
.IX Item "PlainDeleteNode()"
Delete the given node. The node must be a leaf of the tree (may not
have any children) and must have a parent (may not be the root of the
tree).
.ie n .IP """PlainDeleteSubtree(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPlainDeleteSubtree(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PlainDeleteSubtree(node)"
Cut a the given node's subtree and destroy all its nodes.
This macro does not recalculate ordering attributes.
.ie n .IP """NormalizeOrds(listref)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWNormalizeOrds(listref)\fR" 4
.IX Item "NormalizeOrds(listref)"
Adjusts the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute of every node of the list
referenced by the listref argument so that the value for the attribute
corresponds to the order of the node in the list and repaste each node
so that the structural order corresponds with this new numbering.
.Sp
If no numbering \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute is available, all this macro
does is to ensure that the structural order of sibling nodes
corresponds to their order in the given list.
.ie n .IP """SortByOrd(listref)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSortByOrd(listref)\fR" 4
.IX Item "SortByOrd(listref)"
Sort the list of nodes referenced by the listref argumnt according to
the values of the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute.
.ie n .IP """RepasteNode(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRepasteNode(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "RepasteNode(node)"
Cut the given node and paste it immediately on the same parent so that
its structural position between its parent children is brought to
correspondence with the values of the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute.
.ie n .IP """ShiftNodeRightSkipHidden(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWShiftNodeRightSkipHidden(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ShiftNodeRightSkipHidden(node)"
Shift the current node in the tree to the right leaping over all
hidden subtress by modifying the tree structure and value of the
special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute appropriately.
.ie n .IP """ShiftNodeLeftSkipHidden(node,min?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWShiftNodeLeftSkipHidden(node,min?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ShiftNodeLeftSkipHidden(node,min?)"
Shift the current node in the tree to the left leaping over all hidden
subtress by modifying the tree structure and value of the special \s-1FS\s0
numbering attribute appropriately. The optional argument min may be
used to specify the minimum left boundary for the value of the
ordering attribute of node.
.ie n .IP """ShiftNodeRight(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWShiftNodeRight(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ShiftNodeRight(node)"
Shift the current node in the tree to the right by modifying the tree
structure and value of the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute
accordingly.
.ie n .IP """ShiftNodeLeft(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWShiftNodeLeft(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ShiftNodeLeft(node)"
Shift the current node in the tree to the right by modifying the tree
structure and value of the special \s-1FS\s0 numbering attribute
appropriately.
.ie n .IP """GetNodesExceptSubtree(node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGetNodesExceptSubtree(node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "GetNodesExceptSubtree(node)"
Returns the reference to an array containing the whole tree except the
nodes strictly in the subtrees of nodes given in an array referenced
by the parameter. (The returned array does contain the nodes passed in
the parameter.)
.ie n .IP """MoveNode(source\-node,target\-node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWMoveNode(source\-node,target\-node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "MoveNode(source-node,target-node)"
Move the node specified by the first parameter after the node specified by
the second parameter in the ordering on nodes.
.ie n .IP """MoveSubtree(source\-node,target\-node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWMoveSubtree(source\-node,target\-node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "MoveSubtree(source-node,target-node)"
Move the subtree of the node specified by the first parameter after
the node specified by the second parameter in the ordering on
nodes. The subtree of the first argument is made contiguous in the
ordering on nodes, if it happens not to be so. (We use the fact that
the technical root node is always first in the ordering.)
.SS "Helper macros for attributes with list or alternatives of values"
.IX Subsection "Helper macros for attributes with list or alternatives of values"
.ie n .IP """CloneValue(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCloneValue(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CloneValue(value)"
Return an identical deep copy of a given scalar. Useful for copying
attribute values (and any value below them), including structured
attributes, lists or alternatives.
.Sp
Warning: do not apply this macro to an entire Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm> since otherwise
you might result with a copy of the complete tree, schema, etc.
.ie n .IP """IsList(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWIsList(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "IsList(value)"
Check that a given value is a list, i.e. Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """IsAlt(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWIsAlt(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "IsAlt(value)"
Check that a given value is an alternative, i.e. Treex::PML::Alt <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Alt.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """IsSeq(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWIsSeq(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "IsSeq(value)"
Check that a given value is a sequence, i.e. Treex::PML::Seq <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """List(value,value,...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWList(value,value,...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "List(value,value,...)"
Return a new list (Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object) populated with given values.
.ie n .IP """Alt(value,value,...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWAlt(value,value,...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "Alt(value,value,...)"
Return a new alternative (Treex::PML::Alt <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Alt.pm> object) populated with given values.
.ie n .IP """AltV(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWAltV(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "AltV(value)"
If the value is an alternative (i.e. a Treex::PML::Alt <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Alt.pm> object), return
all its values. Otherwise return value.
.ie n .IP """ListV(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWListV(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ListV(value)"
If the value is a list (i.e. a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object), return
all its values. Otherwise return empty (Perl) list.
.ie n .IP """SeqV(value)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSeqV(value)\fR" 4
.IX Item "SeqV(value)"
If the value is a sequence (i.e. a Treex::PML::Seq <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq.pm> object), return all its
elements (Treex::PML::Seq::Element <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq/Element.pm> objects). Otherwise return empty (Perl)
list.
.ie n .IP """AddToAlt(node,attr,value,value...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWAddToAlt(node,attr,value,value...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "AddToAlt(node,attr,value,value...)"
Add given values as alternatives to the current value of
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->{$attr}\*(C'\fR.  If only one value is given and \f(CW\*(C`$node\->{$attr}\*(C'\fR is
empty or same as value, the given value is simply assigned to it. If
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->{$attr}\*(C'\fR is a Treex::PML::Alt <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Alt.pm> object, the new values are simply added
to it. Otherwise, if \f(CW\*(C`$node\->{$attr}\*(C'\fR is a simple value, \f(CW\*(C`$node\->{$attr}\*(C'\fR
is set to a new Treex::PML::Alt <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Alt.pm> object containing the original value as
well as the given values.
.ie n .IP """AddToList(node,attr,value,value,...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWAddToList(node,attr,value,value,...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "AddToList(node,attr,value,value,...)"
Add values to a given attribute. If \f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is not defined or
empty, a new Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> containing given values is created. If
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object, given values are simply added
to it. Error is issued if \f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is defined, non-empty, yet not
a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """AddToListUniq(node,attr,value,value,...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWAddToListUniq(node,attr,value,value,...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "AddToListUniq(node,attr,value,value,...)"
Add values to a given attribute, unless already present among the
current values. If \f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is not defined or empty,
a new Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> containing given values is created. If
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object, given values are
simply added to it. Error is issued if \f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is
defined, non-empty, yet not a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object.
.ie n .IP """AddToSeq(node, attr, name ="" value, name => value,...)> or ""AddToSeq(node, attr, element, ...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWAddToSeq(node, attr, name =\fR value, name => value,...)> or \f(CWAddToSeq(node, attr, element, ...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "AddToSeq(node, attr, name = value, name => value,...)> or AddToSeq(node, attr, element, ...)"
Add elements to a given sequence attribute. If \f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is not defined or
empty, a new Treex::PML::Seq <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq.pm> object containing given name-value pairs (Treex::PML::Seq::Element <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq/Element.pm> objects) is created. If
\&\f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is a Treex::PML::Seq <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq.pm> object, given elements are simply added
to it. Error is issued if \f(CW\*(C`$node\->attr($attr)\*(C'\fR is defined, non-empty, yet not
a Treex::PML::Seq <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Seq.pm> object.
.SS "General-purpose list functions"
.IX Subsection "General-purpose list functions"
.ie n .IP """Index(array\-ref,item)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWIndex(array\-ref,item)\fR" 4
.IX Item "Index(array-ref,item)"
A helper function which returns the index of the first occurence of a
given item in an array. Returns nothing (empty list) if the item is
not found. Note: 'eq' is used for comparison.
.ie n .IP """ListIntersect(array\-ref,array\-ref,...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWListIntersect(array\-ref,array\-ref,...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ListIntersect(array-ref,array-ref,...)"
Compute intersection of given lists. In scalar context returns an
array-ref, in list context returns a list. All duplicities are
removed.
.ie n .IP """ListSubtract(array\-ref, array\-ref)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWListSubtract(array\-ref, array\-ref)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ListSubtract(array-ref, array-ref)"
Return elements occuring in the first list but not in the second list.
In scalar context returns a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object (array-ref), in list
context returns a list. All duplicities are removed.
.ie n .IP """ListUnion(array\-ref, array\-ref, ...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWListUnion(array\-ref, array\-ref, ...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ListUnion(array-ref, array-ref, ...)"
Return union of given lists. In scalar context returns an array-ref,
in list context returns a Treex::PML::List <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/List.pm> object (array-ref). All
duplicities are removed.
.ie n .IP """ListRegroupElements(array\-ref, array\-ref, ...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWListRegroupElements(array\-ref, array\-ref, ...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "ListRegroupElements(array-ref, array-ref, ...)"
This is rotate-matrix like operation. The input is a list of
rows (array-refs each representing a row in a matrix); the output
is a list of columns in the matrix (a list of array-refs, each
representing a column in the matrix).
.SS "GUI-related macros"
.IX Subsection "GUI-related macros"
.ie n .IP """GUI()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWGUI()\fR" 4
.IX Item "GUI()"
Return a reference if running from TrEd, i.e., \s-1GUI\s0 is available;
otherwise return \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR. If running from TrEd the returned value is
a TrEd::Window object representing the currently focused window.
.ie n .IP """CloseGUI()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCloseGUI()\fR" 4
.IX Item "CloseGUI()"
This macro is only available in TrEd. It closes TrEd's main window and
exits.
.ie n .IP """TrEdWindows()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWTrEdWindows()\fR" 4
.IX Item "TrEdWindows()"
Return a list of TrEd::Window objects representing current TrEd
windows.
.ie n .IP """CurrentWindow()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCurrentWindow()\fR" 4
.IX Item "CurrentWindow()"
Return a TrEd::Window object representing the currently focused
window.
.ie n .IP """SetCurrentWindow(win)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSetCurrentWindow(win)\fR" 4
.IX Item "SetCurrentWindow(win)"
Focus a given window.
.ie n .IP """SplitWindowHorizontally(\e%opts?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSplitWindowHorizontally(\e%opts?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "SplitWindowHorizontally(%opts?)"
Split current window horizontally. Returns an object represening the
newly created window.
.Sp
An optional HASHref with the following options can be passed as an argument:
.RS 4
.IP "no_focus => 0|1" 8
.IX Item "no_focus => 0|1"
do not focus the new view (default value is 1)
.IP "no_init => 0|1" 8
.IX Item "no_init => 0|1"
do not initialize the new view with the file, context, etc. from the
current vie (default value is 0)
.IP "no_redraw => 0|1" 8
.IX Item "no_redraw => 0|1"
do not redraw the new view
.IP "ratio => float" 8
.IX Item "ratio => float"
A float value between 0 and 1 indicating the ratio of the height of
the new view to the current height of the active view.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.ie n .IP """SplitWindowVertically()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSplitWindowVertically()\fR" 4
.IX Item "SplitWindowVertically()"
Split current window horizontally. Returns an object represening the
newly created window.
.Sp
An optional HASHref with the following options can be passed as an argument:
.RS 4
.IP "no_focus => 0|1" 8
.IX Item "no_focus => 0|1"
do not focus the new view (default value is 1)
.IP "no_init => 0|1" 8
.IX Item "no_init => 0|1"
do not initialize the new view with the file, context, etc. from the
current vie (default value is 0)
.IP "no_redraw => 0|1" 8
.IX Item "no_redraw => 0|1"
do not redraw the new view
.IP "ratio => float" 8
.IX Item "ratio => float"
A float value between 0 and 1 indicating the ratio of the height of
the new view to the current height of the active view.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.ie n .IP """CloseWindow(win?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCloseWindow(win?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CloseWindow(win?)"
Close a given window, unless it is the last window that exists.  If no
window is given as an argument, try closing the current window.  If
the closed window was focused, then a next sibling window gets focus.
.ie n .IP """CurrentFile(win?)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCurrentFile(win?)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CurrentFile(win?)"
Return a Treex::PML::Document <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Document.pm> object representing the file currently open in a given
TrEd window or in the currently focused window if called without
arguments.
.ie n .IP """CurrentNodeInOtherWindow(win)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWCurrentNodeInOtherWindow(win)\fR" 4
.IX Item "CurrentNodeInOtherWindow(win)"
Return the node currently active in a given window.
.ie n .IP """SetCurrentNodeInOtherWindow(win,node)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSetCurrentNodeInOtherWindow(win,node)\fR" 4
.IX Item "SetCurrentNodeInOtherWindow(win,node)"
Set active node for a given window.
.ie n .IP """InVerticalMode()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWInVerticalMode()\fR" 4
.IX Item "InVerticalMode()"
Return true if the tree is currently displayed in the vertical mode.
.ie n .IP """ToplevelFrame()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWToplevelFrame()\fR" 4
.IX Item "ToplevelFrame()"
Returns the Tk::Toplevel object containing the current window.
.ie n .IP """PrintDialog(...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWPrintDialog(...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "PrintDialog(...)"
See the description in the \*(L"Printing trees\*(R" section.
.ie n .IP """Redraw($win?.$ignoreThis)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRedraw($win?.$ignoreThis)\fR" 4
.IX Item "Redraw($win?.$ignoreThis)"
Force TrEd to immediately redraw the current (or given) window. Hence
TrEd redraws the tree right after an interactively invoked macro
finishes, explicit calls to Redraw macro are needed rather rearly (for
example from a hook). If the flag \f(CW$ignoreThis\fR is used, then current
value of \f(CW$this\fR variable will not be used to determine the current node
of the window (i.e. \f(CW$win\fR\->{currentNode}).
.ie n .IP """Redraw_FSFile()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRedraw_FSFile()\fR" 4
.IX Item "Redraw_FSFile()"
Force TrEd to immediately redraw all windows displaying current
file.
.ie n .IP """Redraw_FSFile_Tree()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRedraw_FSFile_Tree()\fR" 4
.IX Item "Redraw_FSFile_Tree()"
Force TrEd to immediately redraw all windows displaying current
tree.
.ie n .IP """Redraw_All()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRedraw_All()\fR" 4
.IX Item "Redraw_All()"
Force TrEd to immediately redraw all windows.
.ie n .IP """RedrawStatusLine()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRedrawStatusLine()\fR" 4
.IX Item "RedrawStatusLine()"
Force TrEd to immediately redraw status line.
.ie n .IP """EditAttribute(node,attribute)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWEditAttribute(node,attribute)\fR" 4
.IX Item "EditAttribute(node,attribute)"
Open edit attribute \s-1GUI\s0.
.ie n .IP """Undo()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWUndo()\fR" 4
.IX Item "Undo()"
Act as if the user pressed the undo button. Note that this macro also
changes \f(CW$this\fR and \f(CW$root\fR (since undo replaces the current tree with an
in-memory copy).
.Sp
\&\s-1WARNING:\s0 Be aware that calling \fIUndo()\fR from a hook may conflict with
some macros, more specifically, with macros triggering such a hook
(indirectly, i.e. via some \s-1API\s0 call). In a case, changes to \f(CW$this\fR and
\&\f(CW$root\fR caused by \fIUndo()\fR do not propagate to the macro, which in turn
ends up working with incorrect (already replaced) nodes. Thus, if
calling \fIUndo()\fR within a hook, make sure to reset \f(CW$this\fR from
\&\f(CW$grp\fR\->{currentNode} and \f(CW$root\fR from \f(CW$this\fR\->root after all calls from
your macros which may possibly invoke the hook.
.ie n .IP """Redo()""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWRedo()\fR" 4
.IX Item "Redo()"
Act as if the user pressed the undo button. Note that this macro also
changes \f(CW$this\fR and \f(CW$root\fR.
.ie n .IP """SaveUndo(comment)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSaveUndo(comment)\fR" 4
