.IX Subsection "Create/modify keyboard shortcuts"
.ie n .IP """Bind( macro => bind\-options,...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWBind( macro => bind\-options,...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "Bind( macro => bind-options,...)"
This macro can be used to dynamically create keyboard bindings and
menu items for user-defined macros in TrEd. The arguments consist of
one or more (macro => bind-options ) pairs
where macro is a subroutine name or a \s-1CODE\s0 reference and
bind-options is either a keyboard shortcut (e.g. 'Ctrl+a') or a \s-1HASH\s0 references
with the following keys and values (all optional):
.RS 4
.IP "context" 8
.IX Item "context"
the binding context, e.g. the package in which context the macro is
evaluated. Only relevant if the macro is specified by name. If not
given, the caller package is used.
.IP "key" 8
.IX Item "key"
a keyboard binding for the macro (e.g. 'Ctrl+a'); if not given, no
keyboard binding is created.
.IP "menu" 8
.IX Item "menu"
a label to be used for a menu-item created for the macro. If not
given, no menu-item is created for the macro.
.IP "changing_file" 8
.IX Item "changing_file"
if the key \f(CW\*(C`changing_file\*(C'\fR exists in the bind-options hash and its
value is \fIvalue\fR, a call to the macro \f(CW\*(C`ChangignFile(\f(CIvalue\f(CW)\*(C'\fR
is made immediatelly after each invocation of the macro via this
binding.
.RE
.RS 4
.RE
.ie n .IP """UnbindBuiltin(key\-binding)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWUnbindBuiltin(key\-binding)\fR" 4
.IX Item "UnbindBuiltin(key-binding)"
(TrEd only). Remove default TrEd's keybinding for a given key so that
custom macro can be bound to that key.
E.g. UnbindBuiltin('Ctrl+Home'); Note: use with care. Built-in
key-bining once removed cannot be restored (except by restarting TrEd).
.ie n .IP """OverrideBuiltinBinding(context,key\-binding, binding_spec )""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWOverrideBuiltinBinding(context,key\-binding, binding_spec )\fR" 4
.IX Item "OverrideBuiltinBinding(context,key-binding, binding_spec )"
(TrEd only). Get or modify default TrEd's keybinding.
.Sp
The \f(CW\*(C`binding_spec\*(C'\fR argument, if given, must be an array reference with two elements:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&  [ sub { ... }, \*(Aqdescription\*(Aq ]
.Ve
.Sp
\&\s-1WARNING:\s0 You have to be very careful when overriding a builtin
binding, since your code is not called as a macro or a hook! The routine is
called with the following three arguments:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&  $tk_window, $grp\->{framegroup}, $key
.Ve
.Sp
You may obtain \f(CW$grp\fR from the second argument using
\&\f(CW$_\fR[1]\->{currentWindow}.  You should probably call Tk\->break at the end
of your code, so that the event does not propagate. There is no
\&\f(CW$root\fR or \f(CW$this\fR available within the callback.
.Sp
A safer way (with slower execution, though) is to use a macro wrapped
into a \fIMacroCallback()\fR instead of a sub:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\& [ MacroCallback(...), \*(Aqdescription\*(Aq ]
.Ve
.Sp
See \f(CW\*(C`MacroCallback\*(C'\fR macro for details. The macro is called with the
same arguments (appended to a list of arguments provided in
\&\f(CW\*(C`MacroCallback\*(C'\fR). The macro can use all standard macro functions and
variables.
.Sp
If the \f(CW\*(C`context\*(C'\fR argument is a name of a binding context, the binding
is only used in the specific context.  If \f(CW\*(C`context\*(C'\fR is \f(CW\*(Aq*\*(Aq\fR, the
binding applies to all contexts (except for contexts that specifically
overrid it).
.Sp
If called without a binding_spec, the current binding_spec is returned, otherwise
the previous binding_spec is returned.
.Sp
Example (swaps the behavior of normal \f(CW\*(C`left/right\*(C'\fR with \f(CW\*(C`Shift+left/right\*(C'\fR)
.Sp
.Vb 7
\&  my @keys = qw(Left Right);
\&  my %normal = map { $_ => OverrideBuiltinBinding(\*(Aq*\*(Aq,$_) } @keys;
\&  my %shift = map { $_ => OverrideBuiltinBinding(\*(Aq*\*(Aq,"Shift+$_") } @keys;
\&  for (@keys) {
\&    OverrideBuiltinBinding(_\|_PACKAGE_\|_, $_, $shift{$_});
\&    OverrideBuiltinBinding(_\|_PACKAGE_\|_, "Shift+$_", $normal{$_});
\&  }
.Ve
.Sp
Here is another example that changes the Up arrow to move to the
grand-parent instead of a parent:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&  # Using TrEd internals (faster, but prone to changes in the internal API):
\&
\&  OverrideBuiltinBinding(
\&    _\|_PACKAGE_\|_,
\&    \*(AqUp\*(Aq,
\&    [sub { main::currentUp($_[1]) for 1..2 },
\&    \*(AqMove to grand\-parent\*(Aq]);
\&
\&  # Using a macro (slower):
\&
\&  OverrideBuiltinBinding(
\&    _\|_PACKAGE_\|_,
\&    "Up",
\&    [MacroCallback(sub { $this=$this\->parent; $this=$this\->parent if $this }),
\&    \*(AqMove to grand\-parent\*(Aq]);
.Ve
.ie n .IP """MacroCallback(macro_spec,@args)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWMacroCallback(macro_spec,@args)\fR" 4
.IX Item "MacroCallback(macro_spec,@args)"
This macro can be used to safely wrap a given macro into a code that
can be used to override a TrEd builtin or passed as a callback to a Tk
widget.
.Sp
The first argument can take one of the following forms:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&  String:
\&    "macro_name" or "Package\->macro_name"
\&
\&  Anonymous subrutine:
\&    sub { ...code... }
\&
\&  Hash reference:
\&    { \-command => sub { ...code... },
\&      \-changing_file => 0 | 1,
\&      \-contex => \*(AqPackageName\*(Aq
\&    }
\&
\&  Array reference:
\&    [ sub { ..code ...}, arg1, arg2, ...]
.Ve
.Sp
The macro is called with the arguments provided in the macro_spec,
followed by the arguments provided in the call to MacroCallback,
followed by arguments passed by the caller (e.g. TrEd or the Tk
widget).
