.ie n .IP """SetupXPath(function\-mapping...)""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWSetupXPath(function\-mapping...)\fR" 4
.IX Item "SetupXPath(function-mapping...)"
\&\f(CW\*(C`SetupXPath(
            id         => \e&find_node_by_id,
            pos        => \e&node_position,
            attributes => \e&node_attributes_hashref,
            name       => \e&node_name,
            value      => \e&node_value,
            children   => \e&node_children,
            parent     => \e&node_parent,
            lbrother   => \e&node_left_sibling,
            rbrother   => \e&node_right_sibling,
           )\*(C'\fR
.Sp
This macro requires \f(CW\*(C`XML::XPath\*(C'\fR module to be installed.  It adjusts
Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm> \s-1API\s0 to match XPath model based on a given function mapping.  By
default, 'id' is defined to return nothing, 'pos' returns nodes
sentence-ordering position (or depth-first-ordering position if sentord
attribute is not defined), 'attributes' returs a hashref of node's
attributes (actually a Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm> itself), 'name' returns \*(L"node\*(R", 'value'
returns node's value of the special \s-1FS\s0 value attribute, and
\&'children', 'parent', 'lbrother', and 'rbrother' all default to the
respective Treex::PML::Node <http://search.cpan.org/~pajas/Treex-PML/lib/Treex/PML/Node.pm> methods.
.Sp
Usage example:
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`SetupXPath(id    => sub { $hashed_ids{ $_[0] } },
           name  => sub { $_[0]\->{functor} }
           value => sub { $_[0]\->{t_lemma} });\*(C'\fR
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`foreach ($node\->findnodes(q{//ACT/PAT[starts\-with(@tag,"N") or .="ano"]})) {
    # process matching nodes
}\*(C'\fR
